#Text=Sewanee
#Text=Sewanee
#Text=is a small town in south-central Tennessee .
#Text=It is known primarily for its natural scenery and association with the University of the South .
#Text=There are roughly 2,500 residents , of whom about 1,500 are students at the University .
#Text=Sewanee is positioned about halfway between Nashville and Chattanooga .
#Text=The town and the roughly 13,000 acres surrounding it -- all of which are owned directly by the University -- are quaintly called " The Domain " by residents .
#Text=Get in
#Text=Sewanee is accessible primarily by automobile .
#Text=University Avenue ( the town 's primary street ) intersects Tennessee Highway 41A at two locations .
#Text=Some travelers may also take advantage of the small airport nearby .
#Text=Get around
#Text=The town is small enough to be explored on foot or bike , and this is how many residents ( and most University students ) move around .
#Text=Cars are only truly necessary to leave the town and explore the nearby mountain roads .
#Text=See
#Text=The University of the South ( commonly called just " Sewanee " ) is renowned for its scenic campus , which consists largely of pink-sandstone Gothic architecture .
#Text=It is one of a very few American college campuses which attempts Oxford -style architectural principles , though there are plenty of modern buildings which disrupt that atmosphere .
#Text=Of particular interest is the gorgeous All Saints ' Chapel and the University quadrangle .
#Text=The other major attraction in Sewanee is the natural landscape .
#Text=Due to its location on the Cumberland Plateau , there are many scenic vistas overlooking nearby valleys .
#Text=Some are accessible by car ( such as University View on Tennessee Ave. , and Green 's View on Green 's View Rd . ) , but most are accessible only by foot or mountain bike .
#Text=University View and its large Memorial Cross are worth a drive down Tennessee Ave. for any visitor .
#Text=There are also a number of unusual rock formations and other natural oddities in the area , which are outlined in local hiking guides .
#Text=None of the above involve an entry fee , and all can be experienced year-round .
#Text=Do
#Text=Camping and hiking
#Text=are major activities in the area , and can be done comfortably almost year-round .
#Text=The best times of year are the late fall and mid-spring , when the natural beauty is at its peak .
#Text=Camping during the winter is not advisable due to severe weather ( usually involving dense fog and snow ) .
#Text=The mountain trails are generally open to bikers and rock-climbers ; however , it is a good idea to inquire about whether a particular location is suitable for your activity .
#Text=Many trails feature steep drops and climbs that are not practical for biking , and some climbing areas can be tricky or even downright dangerous .
#Text=There are also some accessible caves scattered across the area , but attempting to navigate them without a guide is highly discouraged .
#Text=Questions regarding trail access and other outdoor activities should be directed to the Sewanee Outing Program .
#Text=Most social activities in the area are organized either by the University or local church groups .
#Text=There are also a few local bars which may have musical guests on any given weekend .
#Text=It is worth inquiring whether the University is hosting any special exhibits , performing artists , or lectures during your stay .
#Text=On almost any given day there will be something interesting happening in Sewanee ; however , the scale of these events can vary wildly and many are not open to the public .
#Text=If you arrive during a " dead " time , there is a small movie theater located in the back of Thompson Union on University Ave. that usually shows second-run and foreign films .
#Text=University sports are always an option for entertainment .
#Text=Football games
#Text=have been played in the stadium for well over a century ( making it the oldest field in the South ) , and are a very unusual sight to behold .
#Text=There is also a golf course ( with unusual sandstone outcroppings ) on University Ave. , which is reasonably priced .
#Text=Holidays are generally the best times to visit , as they typically involve community festivals .
#Text=The Fourth of July involves a small parade and fireworks , and usually attracts many people to the area for a few days .
#Text=Christmas , Easter , and University events such as Homecoming , Commencement , and Parents ' Weekend also attract local artisans and performers to provide entertainment .
#Text=The Sewanee Summer Music Center provides concerts on the University of the South campus for five weeks each summer .

#Text=Buy
#Text=There are a few small stores in Sewanee , but most shopping is found in nearby Monteagle .
#Text=The University Bookstore has an exceptional collection of books and gifts , especially for those with academic interests .
#Text=If you are only looking for souvenirs , you can find them in Sewanee ; for " real " shopping , you will need to leave town .
#Text=Sewanee Bookstore
#Text=, 735 University Ave ( across from the intersection with Tennessee Ave. ) , ☏ +1 931-598-1153 .
#Text=An excellent bookstore for students and visitors .
#Text=Features the standard array of college merchandise , as well as a very tasteful book selection .
#Text=The adjacent " Supply Store " offers necessities and food .
#Text=Taylor 's Mercantile
#Text=, 10 University Ave , ☏ +1 931-598-5893 .
#Text=Sells a variety of gifts , flowers , and other miscellaneous items .
#Text=The Lemon Fair
#Text=, 60 University Ave , ☏ +1 931-598-5248 .
#Text=Gift shop that offers a creative mix of homemade and fanciful items .
#Text=A good place to do souvenir shopping .
#Text=Something L 's Art of Jewelry
#Text=Small jewelry shop near the cluster of restaurants .
#Text=Moral Fibers
#Text=In the event that you should need liturgical clothing ( i. e. , you are conducting a religious service and forgot your vestments ) , this is the place to go .
#Text=Otherwise it 's worth peeking in the window just to see the beautiful fabrics .
#Text=Hospitality Shop
#Text=, 1096 University Ave , ☏ +1 931-598-0136 .
#Text=Secondhand store benefiting the local medical clinic .
#Text=Usually a source of unusual clothing and other items .
#Text=Sewanee Market
#Text=.
#Text=28 Lake O'Donnell Rd . , 931-598-5993 .
#Text=Small grocery store at the intersection of University and Hwy 41 .
#Text=Not a large selection ; true grocery shopping is usually done in Monteagle .
#Text=However , the Market is good for immediate needs such as bread , cereal , or beer .
